&lt;p&gt;I believe your issue is that you're getting a &lt;code&gt;NULL&lt;/code&gt; value back from the database, which go translates into &lt;code&gt;nil&lt;/code&gt;. However, you're scanning into an integer, which has no concept of &lt;code&gt;nil&lt;/code&gt;. One thing you can do is scan into a type that implements the &lt;a href="https://golang.org/pkg/database/sql/#Scanner" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;code&gt;sql.Scanner&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; interface (and can handle &lt;code&gt;NULL&lt;/code&gt; values), e.g., &lt;a href="https://golang.org/pkg/database/sql/#NullInt64" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;code&gt;sql.NullInt64&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the example code in the &lt;a href="https://golang.org/pkg/database/sql/#DB.QueryRow" rel="nofollow"&gt;documentation&lt;/a&gt;, I'd assume they have a &lt;code&gt;NOT NULL&lt;/code&gt; constraint on the &lt;code&gt;username&lt;/code&gt; column. I think the reason for this is because they didn't want to lead people to believe that you &lt;em&gt;have&lt;/em&gt; to use NULL-able types across the board.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

